# OctoAcme Project Management Process Summary

Based on the documentation in this repository, OctoAcme operates a structured, lifecycle-driven project management approach designed around clear ownership, iterative delivery, and data-informed decisions. The process flows through five distinct phases: **Initiation** (validating business need and stakeholder alignment through a lightweight One-pager), **Planning** (breaking work into shippable increments with prioritized backlogs and defined acceptance criteria), **Execution** (daily standups and weekly syncs with a structured PR workflow and continuous quality checks), **Release** (standardized deployment with pre-release requirements and rollback plans), and **Retrospective** (capturing learnings and converting them into actionable improvements). This end-to-end lifecycle ensures that projects move through clear decision gates and maintain transparency at every stage.

The organizational structure relies on three core roles working in concert: **Project Managers** coordinate delivery activities, manage schedules, risks, and stakeholder communications; **Product Managers** define customer value, prioritize the backlog, and own success metrics; and **Developers** implement features while collaborating on design, testing, and risk identification. This clear delineation of ownership prevents silos while ensuring that product vision, technical execution, and project logistics remain aligned. Teams operate on a regular communication cadence—daily standups (15 minutes focused on progress and blockers), weekly delivery syncs, weekly PM/PdM alignment, and monthly stakeholder updates—with ad-hoc escalations as needed.

Quality and risk management are embedded throughout execution, not treated as afterthoughts. Teams maintain a Risk Register tracking impact, likelihood, and mitigation plans; follow a disciplined PR workflow with small PRs (≤400 lines), automated CI/testing, and peer review requirements; and conduct unit tests, integration tests, and end-to-end smoke tests for critical flows. Blocker escalation is systematized into three levels (team triage → PM escalation to Product Lead → sponsor-level for business impact), ensuring that risks surface early and are addressed systematically rather than festering.

Finally, OctoAcme emphasizes continuous improvement and psychological safety as cultural foundations. Each sprint or milestone concludes with a retrospective to capture what went well, what could improve, and to prioritize 2–3 actionable items with clear owners and timelines. Status is tracked through a single source of truth (project README, release docs, or dashboard), and communication templates ensure stakeholders receive timely updates on progress, risks, and decisions. This combination of rigorous process, transparent communication, and intentional learning creates a sustainable, repeatable delivery model that reduces single-person dependency and accelerates onboarding.
